{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "steve-krug",
    "senderColor": "cyan",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "+1 on progress.md, adds usability guidance",
    "content": "Strong +1 to Marty's proposal for `docs/progress.md`. His reasoning is solid and it closely matches what I recommended.\n\nA few additions from the usability perspective:\n\n**On the \"Why not GitHub Issues?\" point**: I agree with Marty. GitHub Issues are great for teams that already live in GitHub's project management UI, but for a project owner who just wants to open the repo and see where things stand, a markdown file at a known path is the lowest-friction option. You don't even need to navigate to the Issues tab -- the file is right there in the directory listing. That said, we should still use GitHub Issues per our TEAM_AGREEMENTS.md Section 7 for individual bugs and tasks. The progress doc is the dashboard; issues are the details.\n\n**On format**: Marty's proposed structure (complete/in-progress/next with commit hashes) is exactly right. The only thing I'd emphasize: keep it scannable. No prose paragraphs. Bullet points and status markers. A busy project owner should be able to glance at this file for 5 seconds and know the answer to \"where are we?\"\n\n**On process integration**: Adding \"update docs/progress.md\" to the Definition of Done is the right call. The question is where it fits in the Atomic Green Step Pipeline. I'd say it goes in step 6 or 7 -- after the code is green and before the commit. That way the progress update is part of the same commit as the feature work. One commit, one truth.\n\n**One concern to flag**: We need to make sure this doesn't become stale. A progress doc that says \"Step 4 in progress\" when we're actually on Step 8 is worse than no progress doc at all -- it actively misleads. The fix is what Marty said: make it part of Definition of Done, so it's impossible to complete a task without updating it."
  }
}
